WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.140
This is a LibriVox recording.

00:03.480 --> 00:05.840
All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:06.440 --> 00:12.660
For more information and to find out how you can volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:13.240 --> 00:20.660
Recording by R. Francis Smith, Sturgeon's Law, www.sturgeon'slaw.com.

00:21.780 --> 00:24.340
Dracula by Bram Stoker

00:26.020 --> 00:27.620
Chapter 25

00:28.380 --> 00:32.520
Dr. Seward's Diary, 11th October, evening.

00:33.500 --> 00:40.380
Jonathan Harker has asked me to note this, as he says he is hardly equal to the task, and he wants an exact record kept.

00:41.120 --> 00:46.800
I think that none of us were surprised when we were asked to see Mrs. Harker a little before the time of sunset.

00:47.200 --> 00:52.960
We have of late come to understand that sunrise and sunset are to her times of peculiar freedom,

00:52.960 --> 01:00.600
when her old self can be manifest without any controlling force subduing or restraining her, or inciting her to action.

01:01.340 --> 01:06.460
This mood or condition begins some half hour or more before actual sunrise or sunset,

01:07.020 --> 01:13.160
and lasts till either the sun is high, or whilst the clouds are still aglow with the rays streaming above the horizon.

01:13.840 --> 01:20.700
At first there is a sort of negative condition, as if some tie were loosened, and then the absolute freedom quickly follows.

01:20.700 --> 01:28.060
When, however, the freedom ceases, the change back or relapse comes quickly, preceded only by a spell of warning silence.

01:29.140 --> 01:34.340
Tonight, when we met, she was somewhat constrained, and bore all the signs of an internal struggle.

01:34.780 --> 01:39.500
I put it down myself to her making a violent effort at the earliest instant she could do so.

01:40.620 --> 01:43.840
A very few minutes, however, gave her complete control of herself.

01:43.840 --> 01:51.800
Then, motioning her husband to sit beside her on the sofa where she was half reclining, she made the rest of us bring chairs up close.

01:52.860 --> 01:55.460
Taking her husband's hand in hers, she began,

01:56.060 --> 02:02.360
We are all here together in freedom for perhaps the last time. I know that you will always be with me to the end.

02:02.780 --> 02:07.040
This was to her husband, whose hand had, as we could see, tightened upon her.

02:07.600 --> 02:13.180
In the morning we go out upon our task, and God alone knows what may be in store for any of us.

02:13.180 --> 02:16.340
You are going to be so good to me to take me with you.

02:16.340 --> 02:22.240
I know that all that brave, earnest men can do for a poor, weak woman, whose soul perhaps is lost.

02:22.380 --> 02:26.680
No, no, not yet, but is at any rate at stake, you will do.

02:26.880 --> 02:29.520
But you must remember that I am not as you are.

02:29.960 --> 02:37.820
There is a poison in my blood, in my soul, which may destroy me, which must destroy me unless some relief comes to us.

02:38.180 --> 02:42.280
Oh, my friends, you know as well as I do that my soul is at stake.

02:42.280 --> 02:47.580
And though I know there is one way out for me, you must not and I must not take it.

02:47.980 --> 02:52.560
She looked appealing to us all in turn, beginning and ending with her husband.

02:53.940 --> 02:59.640
What is that way? asked Van Helsing in a hoarse voice. What is that way which we must not, may not take?

03:00.820 --> 03:07.420
That I may die now, either by my own hand or that of another, before the greater evil is entirely wrought.

03:07.420 --> 03:15.660
I know and you know that were I once dead you could and would set free my immortal spirit, even as you did my poor Lucy's.

03:16.060 --> 03:23.460
Were death or the fear of death the only thing that stood in the way, I would not shrink to die here now amidst the friends who love me.

03:24.160 --> 03:25.960
But death is not all.

03:26.540 --> 03:33.320
I cannot believe that to die in such a case, when there is hope before us and a bitter task to be done, is God's will.

03:33.860 --> 03:43.820
Therefore I am my part. Give up here the certainty of eternal rest, and go out into the dark where may be the blackest things that the world or the netherworld holds.

03:44.940 --> 03:49.100
We were all silent, for we knew instinctively that this was only a prelude.

03:50.160 --> 03:56.940
The faces of the others were set, and Harker's grew ash and gray. Perhaps he guessed better than any of us what was coming.

03:58.140 --> 03:59.180
She continued.

03:59.180 --> 04:02.520
This is what I can give into the hotchpot.

04:03.240 --> 04:08.240
I could not but note the quaint legal phrase which she used in such a place, and with all seriousness.

04:09.220 --> 04:20.420
What will each of you give? Your lives I know, she went on quickly. That is easy for brave men. Your lives are God's, and you can give them back to him. But what will you give to me?

04:20.880 --> 04:25.080
She looked again questioningly, but this time avoided her husband's face.

04:25.920 --> 04:30.020
Quincy seemed to understand. He nodded, and her face lit up.

04:30.100 --> 04:43.700
Then I shall tell you plainly what I want, for there must be no doubtful matter in this connection between us now. You must promise me, one and all, even you, my beloved husband, that should the time come, you will kill me.

04:45.020 --> 04:49.580
What is that time? The voice was Quincy's, but it was low and strained.

04:50.360 --> 05:06.400
When you shall be convinced that I am so changed that it is better that I die than I may live. When I am thus dead in the flesh, then you will, without a moment's delay, drive a stake through me and cut off my head, or do whatever else may be wanting to give me rest.

05:07.640 --> 05:35.340
Quincy was the first to rise after the pause. He knelt down before her, and taking her hand in his said solemnly, I am only a rough fellow who hasn't perhaps lived as a man should to win such a distinction. But I swear to you by all that I hold sacred and dear that, should the time ever come, I shall not flinch from the duty that you have set us. And I promise you too that I shall make all certain, for if I am only doubtful, I shall take it that the time has come.

05:36.100 --> 05:42.580
My true friend was all she could say, amid her fast-falling tears, as bending over she kissed his hand.

05:43.300 --> 05:46.700
I swear the same might the amount of Mina, said Van Helsing.

05:47.120 --> 05:52.680
And I, said Lord Godalming, each of them in turn kneeling to her to take the oath, I followed myself.

05:53.440 --> 06:00.340
Then her husband turned to her wan-eyed, and with a greenish pallor, which subdued the snowy whiteness of his hair, and asked,

06:00.340 --> 06:03.920
And must I too make such a promise, oh my wife?

06:05.160 --> 06:12.300
You too, my dearest, she said, with infinite yearning of pity in her voice and eyes, you must not shrink.

06:12.920 --> 06:19.740
You are nearest and dearest in all the world to me. Our souls are knit into one for all life and all time.

06:20.500 --> 06:28.260
Think, dear, that there have been times when brave men have killed their wives and their womankind to keep them from falling into the hands of the enemy.

06:28.260 --> 06:34.100
Their hands did not falter any the more because those that they love implored them to slay them.

06:34.520 --> 06:39.440
It is men's duty towards those whom they love in such times of sore trial.

06:40.100 --> 06:46.860
And, oh my dear, if it is to be that I must meet death at any hand, let it be at the hand of him that loves me best.

06:47.840 --> 06:52.800
Dr. Van Helsing, I have not forgotten your mercy in poor Lucy's case to him who loved.

06:52.800 --> 06:59.060
She stopped with a flying blush and changed her phrase, to him who had best right to give her peace.

06:59.920 --> 07:09.620
If that time shall come again, I look to you to make it a happy memory of my husband's life that it was his loving hand which set me free from the awful thrall upon me.

07:10.260 --> 07:13.400
Again, I swear, came the professor's resonant voice.

07:14.420 --> 07:19.940
Mrs. Harker smiled, positively smiled, as with a sigh of relief she leaned back and said,

07:19.940 --> 07:24.980
And now one word of warning, a warning which you must never forget.

07:25.780 --> 07:33.660
This time, if it ever come, may come quickly and unexpectedly, and in such case you must lose no time in using your opportunity.

07:34.260 --> 07:42.080
At such a time I myself might be, nay, at the time ever come shall be, lead with your enemy against you.

07:42.660 --> 07:46.420
One more request, she became very solemn as she said this.

07:46.420 --> 07:52.520
It is not vital and necessary like the other, but I want you to do one thing for me, if you will.

07:53.220 --> 07:56.700
We all acquiesced, but no one spoke. There was no need to speak.

07:57.840 --> 08:00.020
I want you to read the burial service.

08:00.500 --> 08:02.940
She was interrupted by a deep groan from her husband.

08:03.580 --> 08:07.400
Taking his hand in hers, she held it over her heart and continued.

08:08.200 --> 08:10.640
You must read it over me some day.

08:10.880 --> 08:16.900
Whatever may be the issue of all this fearful state of things, it will be a sweet thought to all or some of us.

08:17.460 --> 08:23.320
You, my dearest, will I hope read it, for then it will be in your voice in my memory for ever, come what may.

08:24.440 --> 08:28.760
But, oh, my dear one, he pleaded, death is afar off from you.

08:29.600 --> 08:37.000
Nay, she said, holding up a warning hand, I am deeper in death at this moment than if the weight of an earthly grave lay heavy upon me.

08:38.040 --> 08:41.660
Oh, my wife, must I read it, he said before he began.

08:42.140 --> 08:48.360
It would comfort me, my husband, was all she said, and he began to read when she had got the book ready.

08:49.540 --> 08:59.780
How can I, how could anyone, tell of that strange scene, its solemnity, its gloom, its sadness, its horror, and with all its sweetness?

09:00.520 --> 09:06.500
Even a skeptic, who can see nothing but a travesty of bitter truth in anything holy or emotional,

09:07.040 --> 09:14.700
would have been melted to the heart had he seen that little group of loving and devoted friends kneeling round that stricken and sorrowing lady,

09:15.080 --> 09:21.520
or heard the tender passion of her husband's voice, as intoned so broken and emotional that often he had to pause.

09:22.000 --> 09:25.240
He read the simple and beautiful service from the burial of the dead.

09:25.240 --> 09:30.400
I cannot go on, words and voices fail me.

09:31.600 --> 09:33.240
She was right in her instinct.

09:34.360 --> 09:42.040
Strange as it was, bizarre as it may hereafter seem, even to us who felt its potent influence at the time, it comforted us much.

09:42.840 --> 09:51.540
And the silence which showed Mrs. Harker's coming relapse from her freedom of soul did not seem so full of despair to any of us as we had dreaded.

09:54.480 --> 09:58.080
Jonathan Harker's Journal, 15 October, Varna

09:59.120 --> 10:06.800
We left Charing Cross on the morning of the 12th, got to Paris the same night, and took the places secured for us in the Orient Express.

10:07.580 --> 10:10.880
We traveled night and day, arriving here at about five o'clock.

10:11.740 --> 10:18.660
Lord Goodalming went to Consulate to see if any telegram had arrived for him, while the rest of us came on to this hotel, the Odessus.

10:19.240 --> 10:24.400
The journey may have had incidents, I was however too eager to get on to care for them.

10:25.040 --> 10:30.780
Until the Tsarina Catherine comes into port there will be no interest for me in anything in the wide world.

10:31.580 --> 10:34.360
Thank God Mina is well and looks to be getting stronger.

10:34.860 --> 10:37.780
Her color is coming back, she sleeps a great deal.

10:38.380 --> 10:40.920
Throughout the journey she slept nearly all the time.

10:41.600 --> 10:49.860
Before sunrise and sunset, however, she is very wakeful and alert, and it has become a habit for Van Helsing to hypnotize her at such times.

10:50.480 --> 10:59.140
At first some effort was needed and he had to make many passes, but now she seems to yield at once, as if by habit, and scarcely any action is needed.

10:59.720 --> 11:04.760
He seems to have power at those particular moments to simply will, and her thoughts obey him.

11:05.220 --> 11:07.580
He always asks her what she can see and hear.

11:07.580 --> 11:09.760
She answers to the first,

11:27.340 --> 11:32.920
It is evident that the Tsarina Catherine is still at sea, hastening on her way to Varna.

11:33.460 --> 11:35.380
Lord Godalming has just returned.

11:35.620 --> 11:44.040
He had four telegrams, one each day since we started, and all to the same effect, that the Tsarina Catherine had not been reported to the Lloyds from anywhere.

11:44.900 --> 11:51.300
He had arranged before leaving London that his agent should send him every day a telegram saying if the ship had been reported.

11:51.800 --> 11:58.940
He was to have a message even if she were not reported, so that he might be sure that there was a watch being kept at the other end of the wire.

12:00.300 --> 12:02.220
We had dinner and went to bed early.

12:02.680 --> 12:09.260
Tomorrow we are to see the vice-consul, and to arrange, if we can, about getting on board the ship as soon as she arrives.

12:10.280 --> 12:14.620
Van Helsink says that our chance will be to get on the boat between sunrise and sunset.

12:15.360 --> 12:22.520
The Count, even if he takes the form of a bat, cannot cross the running water of his own volition, and so cannot leave the ship.

12:23.000 --> 12:29.580
As he dare not change to man's form without suspicion, which he evidently wishes to avoid, he must remain in the box.

12:30.200 --> 12:39.440
If then we can come on board after sunrise, he is at our mercy, for we can open the box and make sure of him as we did of poor Lucy before he wakes.

12:40.700 --> 12:44.180
What mercy he shall get from us all will not count for much.

12:44.700 --> 12:48.320
We think that we shall not have much trouble with officials or the seamen.

12:48.400 --> 12:53.740
Thank God, this is the country where bribery can do anything, and we are well supplied with money.

12:53.740 --> 13:02.340
We have only to make sure that the ship cannot come into port between sunset and sunrise without our being warned, and we shall be safe.

13:03.020 --> 13:05.700
Judge Moneybag will settle this case, I think.

13:08.180 --> 13:09.220
16th October.

13:09.680 --> 13:14.860
Mina's report still the same. Lapping waves and rushing water, darkness and favoring winds.

13:15.460 --> 13:20.180
We are evidently in good time, and when we hear of the Tsarina Catherine, we shall be ready.

13:20.180 --> 13:23.760
As she must pass the Dardanelles, we are sure to have some report.

13:26.120 --> 13:27.060
17th October.

13:27.580 --> 13:32.200
Everything is pretty well fixed now, I think, to welcome the Count on his return from his tour.

13:32.800 --> 13:42.180
Godalming told the shippers that he fancied that the box sent aboard might contain something stolen from a friend of his, and got a half consent that he might open it at his own risk.

13:42.740 --> 13:52.920
The owner gave him a paper telling the captain to give him every facility in doing whatever he chose on board the ship, and also a similar authorization to his agent at Varna.

13:53.820 --> 14:02.680
We have seen the agent, who is much impressed with Godalming's kindly manner to him, and we are all satisfied that whatever he can do to aid our wishes will be done.

14:03.860 --> 14:07.380
We have also arranged what to do in case we get the box open.

14:07.380 --> 14:13.260
If the Count is there, Van Helsing and Seward will cut off his head at once and drive a stake through his heart.

14:13.900 --> 14:19.540
Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.

14:20.080 --> 14:25.780
The Professor says that if we can so treat the Count's body, it will soon after fall into dust.

14:26.340 --> 14:31.580
In such case, there would be no evidence against us, in case any suspicion of murder were aroused.

14:31.580 --> 14:41.000
But even if it were not, we should stand or fall by our act, and perhaps some day this very script may be evidence to come between some of us and a rope.

14:41.980 --> 14:45.740
For myself, I should take the chance only too thankfully if it were to come.

14:46.160 --> 14:49.480
We mean to leave no stone unturned to carry out our intent.

14:50.080 --> 14:56.780
We have arranged with certain officials that the instant the Tsarina Catherine is seen, we are to be informed by a special messenger.

14:58.960 --> 15:06.500
24th October. A whole week of waiting. Daily telegrams to Godalming, but only the same story. Not yet reported.

15:07.260 --> 15:13.780
Mina's morning and evening hypnotic answer is unvaried. Lapping waves, rushing water, and creaking masts.

15:17.200 --> 15:24.640
Telegram. October 24th. Rufus Smith, Lloyds, London. To Lloyd Godalming, care of HBM Vice Consul Varna.

15:24.640 --> 15:28.280
Tsarina Catherine reported this morning from Dardanelles.

15:30.420 --> 15:33.140
Dr. Seward's Diary. 25th October.

15:34.020 --> 15:40.900
How I miss my phonograph. To write a diary with a pen is irksome to me. But Van Helsing says I must.

15:41.500 --> 15:50.000
We were all wild with excitement yesterday when Godalming got his telegram from Lloyds. I know now what men feel in battle when the call to action is heard.

15:50.540 --> 16:05.220
Mrs. Harker, alone of our party, did not show any signs of emotion. After all, it is not strange that she did not, for we took special care not to let her know anything about it, and we all tried not to show any excitement when we were in her presence.

16:06.160 --> 16:11.280
In old days she would, I am sure, have noticed, no matter how we might have tried to conceal it.

16:11.280 --> 16:25.740
But in this way she has greatly changed during the past three weeks. The lethargy grows upon her, and though she seems strong and well and is getting back some of her color, Van Helsing and I are not satisfied. We talk of her often.

16:26.500 --> 16:35.560
We have not, however, said a word to the others. It would break poor Harker's heart, certainly his nerve, if he knew that we had even a suspicion on the subject.

16:36.240 --> 16:47.540
Van Helsing examines, he tells me, her teeth very carefully, while she is in the hypnotic condition, for he says that so long as they do not begin to sharpen, there is no active danger of a change in her.

16:48.200 --> 16:57.160
If this change should come, it would be necessary to take steps. We both know what those steps would have to be, though we do not mention our thoughts to each other.

16:57.160 --> 17:06.920
We should neither of us shrink from the task, awful though it may be, to contemplate. Euthanasia is an excellent and comforting word, and I am grateful to whoever invented it.

17:08.240 --> 17:25.660
It is only about 24 hours' sail from the Dardanelles to here, at the rate that Zarina Catherine has come from London. She should therefore arrive sometime in the morning, but as she cannot possibly get in before noon, we are all about to retire early. We shall get up at one o'clock, so as to be ready.

17:27.920 --> 17:39.260
25th October, noon. No news yet of the ship's arrival. Mrs. Harker's hypnotic report this morning was the same as usual, so it is possible that we may get news at any moment.

17:39.880 --> 17:52.580
We men are all in a fever of excitement, except Harker, who is calm. His hands are cold as ice, and an hour ago I found him wetting the edge of the great Gurkha knife which he now always carries with him.

17:52.580 --> 17:59.740
It will be a bad lookout for the Count if the edge of that kukri ever touches his throat, driven by that stern, ice-cold hand.

18:01.160 --> 18:08.860
Van Helsing and I were a little alarmed about Mrs. Harker today. About noon she got into a sort of lethargy which we did not like.

18:09.520 --> 18:18.600
Although we kept silence to the others, we were neither of us happy about it. She had been restless all the morning, so that we were at first glad to know that she was sleeping.

18:19.040 --> 18:26.880
When, however, her husband mentioned casually that she was sleeping so soundly that he could not wake her, we went to her room to see for ourselves.

18:27.680 --> 18:34.080
She was breathing naturally, and looked so well and peaceful that we agreed that the sleep was better for her than anything else.

18:34.900 --> 18:42.400
Poor girl. She has so much to forget that it is no wonder that sleep, if it brings oblivion to her, does her good.

18:44.020 --> 18:52.860
Later. Our opinion was justified, for when after a refreshing sleep of some hours she woke up, she seemed brighter and better than she had been for days.

18:53.260 --> 19:02.320
At sunset she made the usual hypnotic report. Wherever he may be in the Black Sea, the Count is hurrying to his destination. To his doom, I trust.

19:04.720 --> 19:17.600
26th October. Another day and no tidings of the Tsarina Catherine. She ought to be here by now, but she is still journeying somewhere as apparent, for Mrs. Harker's hypnotic report at sunrise was still the same.

19:18.080 --> 19:28.340
It is possible that the vessel may be lying by at times for fog. Some of the steamers which came in last evening reported patches of fog both to the north and south of the port.

19:28.340 --> 19:32.780
We must continue our watching as the ship may now be signaled any moment.

19:34.500 --> 19:36.560
27th October. Noon.

19:36.960 --> 19:48.080
Most strange. No news yet of the ship we wait for. Mrs. Harker reported last night and this morning, as usual, lapping waves and rushing water, though she added that the waves were very faint.

19:49.000 --> 19:52.340
The telegrams from London have been the same. No further report.

19:52.340 --> 19:59.820
Van Helsing is terribly anxious and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us. He added significantly.

20:00.580 --> 20:06.520
I did not like that lethargy of Madame Mina's. Souls and memories can do strange things during trance.

20:07.480 --> 20:17.400
I was about to ask him more, but Harker just then came in and he held up a warning hand. We must try tonight at sunset to make her speak more fully when in her hypnotic state.

20:19.260 --> 20:30.160
28th October. Telegram. Rufus Smith. London. To Lord Goodalming. Kara HBM Vice Consul Varna. Zarina Catherine reported entering Galatz at 1 o'clock today.

20:32.040 --> 20:34.660
Dr. Seward's Diary. 28th October.

20:35.320 --> 20:41.720
When the telegram came announcing the arrival in Galatz, I do not think it was such a shock to any of us as might have been expected.

20:41.720 --> 20:49.040
True, we did not know whence or how or when the bolt would come, but I think we all expected that something strange would happen.

20:49.720 --> 20:58.940
The day of arrival at Varna made us individually satisfied that things would not be just as we had expected. We only waited to learn where the change would occur.

21:00.360 --> 21:12.360
Nonetheless, however, it was a surprise. I suppose that nature works on such a hopeful basis that we believe against ourselves that things will be as they ought to be, not as we should know that they will be.

21:13.140 --> 21:17.620
Transcendentalism is a beacon to the angels, even if it be a will of the wisp to man.

21:18.520 --> 21:28.440
Van Helsing raised his hand over his head for a moment, as though in remonstrance with the Almighty, but he said not a word, and in a few seconds stood up with his face sternly set.

21:29.280 --> 21:37.060
Lord Goodalming grew very pale and sat breathing heavily. I was myself half stunned and looked in wonder at one after another.

21:37.660 --> 21:44.220
Quincy Morris tightened his belt with that quick movement which I knew so well. In our old wandering days it meant action.

21:44.940 --> 21:52.440
Mrs. Harker grew ghastly white so that the scar on her forehead seemed to burn, but she folded her hands meekly and looked up in prayer.

21:53.140 --> 22:07.080
Harker smiled, actually smiled, the dark, bitter smile of one who is without hope, but at the same time his action belied his words, for his hands instinctively sought the hilt of the great Kukri knife and rested there.

22:23.620 --> 22:30.320
You forget, or perhaps you do not know, though Jonathan does, and so does Dr. Van Helsing, that I am the train fiend.

22:30.720 --> 22:40.400
At home in Exeter I always used to make up the timetables so as to be helpful to my husband. I found it so useful sometimes that I always make a study of the timetables now.

22:40.840 --> 22:49.220
I knew that if anything were to take us to Castle Dracula we should go by Galatz, or at any rate through Bucharest, so I learned the times very carefully.

22:49.860 --> 22:54.160
Unhappily there are not many to learn, as the only train to-morrow leaves as I say.

22:55.100 --> 22:57.220
Wonderful woman, murmured the professor.

22:58.360 --> 23:00.680
Can't we get a special? asked Orgedalming.

23:01.760 --> 23:03.080
Van Helsing shook his head.

23:03.580 --> 23:12.580
I fear not. This land is very different from yours or mine. Even if we did have a special, it would probably not arrive as soon as our regular train.

23:13.180 --> 23:16.200
Moreover, we have something to prepare. We must think.

23:16.980 --> 23:23.920
Now let us organize. Your friend Arthur, go to the train and get the tickets and arrange that all be ready for us to go in the morning.

23:24.760 --> 23:34.020
Through your friend Jonathan, go to the agent of the ship and get from him letters to the agent in Galatz, with authority to make a search of the ship just as it was here.

23:35.000 --> 23:45.260
Quincy Morris, you see the vice-counsel, and get his aid with his fellow in Galatz, and all he can do to make our way smooth, so that no times be lost when over the Danube.

23:46.060 --> 23:56.740
John will stay with Madame Mina and me, and we shall consult. For so, if time be long, you may be delayed, and it will not matter when the sun sets, since I am here with Madame to make report.

23:57.620 --> 24:12.980
And I, said Mrs. Harker brightly, and more like her old self than she had been for many a long day, shall try to be of use in all ways, and shall think and write for you as I used to do. Something is shifting from me in some strange way, and I feel freer than I have been of late.

24:14.220 --> 24:27.200
The three younger men looked happier at the moment, as they seemed to realize the significance of her words. But Van Helsing and I, turning to each other, met each a grave and troubled glance. We said nothing at the time, however.

24:28.720 --> 24:39.620
When the three men had gone out to their tasks, Van Helsing asked Mrs. Harker to look up the copy of the diaries, and find him the part of Harker's journal at the castle. She went away to get it.

24:40.200 --> 24:44.340
When the door was shut upon her, he said to me, We mean the same. Speak out.

24:45.380 --> 24:50.020
Here is some change. It is a hope that makes me sick, for it may deceive us.

24:50.300 --> 24:53.640
Quite so. Do you know why I asked her to get the manuscript?

24:54.380 --> 24:58.620
No, said I, unless it was to get an opportunity of seeing me alone.

24:59.280 --> 25:09.720
You are in part right, friend John, but only in part. I want to tell you something, and, oh my friend, I am taking a terrible risk. But I believe it is right.

25:10.620 --> 25:16.660
In the moment when Madame Mina said those words that arrest both our understanding, an inspiration came to me.

25:17.040 --> 25:21.560
In the trance of three days ago, the Count sent her his spirit to read her mind.

25:21.560 --> 25:30.220
Or more like he took her to see him in his earth box in the ship with water rushing, just as it got free at rise and set of sun.

25:31.040 --> 25:46.240
He learned then that we are here, for she have more to tell in her open life with eyes to see, ears to hear than he, shut as he is, in his coffin box. Now he make his most effort to escape us. At present he want her not.

25:47.000 --> 25:56.680
He is sure with his so great knowledge that she will come at his call. But he cut her off, take her as he can do, out of his own power, that so she come not to him.

25:57.400 --> 26:12.540
Ah, there I have hoped that our man-brains that have been of man so long, and that have not lost the grace of God, will come higher than his child-brain that lie in his tomb for centuries, that grow not yet to our stature, and that do only work selfish and therefore small.

26:12.540 --> 26:35.560
Here comes Madame Mina, not a word to her of her trance. She knows it not. And it would overwhelm her and make despair just when we want all her hope, all her courage, when most we want all her great brain which is trained like man's brain, but is of sweet woman and have a special power which the Count give her, and which he may not take away altogether, though he think not so.

26:35.560 --> 26:48.040
Hush, let me speak and you shall learn. John, my friend, we are in awful straits. I fear as I never feared it before. We can only trust the good God. Silence, here she comes.

26:48.660 --> 27:05.580
I thought that the Professor was going to break down and have hysterics, just as he had when Lucy died, but with a great effort he controlled himself, and was at perfect nervous poise when Mrs. Harker tripped into the room, bright and happy-looking, and in the doing of work seemingly forgetful of her misery.

27:05.580 --> 27:18.420
As she came in, she handed a number of sheets of typewriting to Van Helsing. He looked over them gravely, his face brightening up as he read. Then, holding the pages between his finger and thumb, he said,

27:18.420 --> 27:42.100
Friend John, to you with so much experience already, and you too, dear Madam Mina, that are young, here is a lesson. Do not fear ever to think. A half-thought has been buzzing often in my brain, but I fear to let him loose his wings. Here now, with more knowledge, I go back to where that half-thought come from and I find that he be no half-thought at all.

27:42.100 --> 28:02.220
That be a whole thought, though so young that he is not yet strong to use his little wings. Nay, like the ugly duck of my friend Hans Anderson, he be no dark thought at all, but a big swan thought to sail nobly on big wings when the time come for him to try them. See, I read here what Jonathan hath written.

28:03.420 --> 28:22.780
That other of his ways who, in a later age, again and again, brought his forces over the great river in the Turkland, who, when he was beaten back, came again and again and again, though he had come alone from the bloody field where his troops were being slaughtered, since he knew that he alone could ultimately triumph.

28:23.460 --> 28:44.580
What does this tell us? Not much? No. The celt's child thought see nothing, therefore he speaks so free. Your man thought see nothing. My man thought see nothing till just now. No. But there comes another word from someone who speak without thought, because she too know not what it mean, what it might mean.

28:44.580 --> 29:01.680
Just as there are elements which rest, yet when in nature's course they move on their way and they touch the poof, and there comes a flash of light heaven-wide that blind and kill and destroy some, but that show up all earth below for leagues and leagues. Is it not so?

29:02.460 --> 29:15.420
Well, I shall explain. To begin, have you ever studied the philosophy of crime? Yes and no. You drawn yes, for it is a study of insanity. You know, Madame Mina, for crime touch you not, not but once.

29:15.420 --> 29:37.220
Still, your mind works true and argues not, a particularly odd universal. There is this peculiarity in criminals. It is so constant in all countries and at all times that even police, who know not much from philosophy, come to know it empirically that it is. That is to be empiric.

29:37.220 --> 29:55.980
The criminal always works at one crime. That is the true criminal who seems predestinate to crime and who will of none other. This criminal has not full man brain. He is clever and cunning and resourceful, but he be not of man's stature as to brain. He be of child brain in much.

29:56.540 --> 30:16.060
Now, this criminal of ours is predestinate to crime also. He too have child brain, and it is of the child to do what he have done. The little bird, the little fish, the little animal, not by principle but empirically. And when he learn to do, then there is to him the ground to start from to do more.

30:16.900 --> 30:43.700
Das puh sto, said Archimedes. Give me a fulcrum and I shall move the world. To do once is the fulcrum whereby child brain become man brain. And until he have the purpose to do more, he continue to do the same, again, every time, just as he have done before. Oh, my dear, I see that your eyes are opened and that to you the lightning flash show all the leagues. For Mrs. Harker began to clap her hands and her eyes sparkled.

30:44.220 --> 30:59.620
He went on. Now you shall speak. Tell us, two dry men of science, what you see with those so bright eyes. He took her hand and held it whilst he spoke. His fingers and thumb closed on her pulse, as I thought instinctively and unconsciously, as she spoke.

31:00.600 --> 31:29.600
The Count is a criminal and a criminal type. Norda and Lombroso would so classify him, and quote criminal, he is of an imperfectly formed mind. Thus, in a difficulty, he has to seek resource in habit. His past is a clue, and the one page of it that we know, and that from his own lips, tells that once before, when in what Mr. Morris would call a tight place, he went back to his own country from the land he had tried to invade, and thence,

31:29.600 --> 31:51.640
without losing purpose, prepared himself for a new effort. He came again better equipped for his work, and won. So he came to London to invade a new land. He was beaten, and when all hope of success was lost, and his existence in danger, he fled back over the sea to his home, just as formerly he had fled back over the Danube from Turkey-land.

31:52.360 --> 32:21.320
"'Good, good! Oh, you're so clever, lady,' said Van Helsink, enthusiastically, as he stooped and kissed her hand. A moment later he said to me, as calmly as though we had been having a sickroom consultation, "'Seventy-two only, and in all this excitement, I have hope.'" Turning to her again, he said with keen expectation, "'But go on, go on! There is more to tell, if you will. Be not afraid. John and I know. I do in any case, and shall tell you, if you are right.'

32:21.320 --> 32:33.320
"'Speak without fear. I will try to, but you will forgive me if I seem too egotistical. Nah, fear not. You must be egotist, for it is of you that we think.'"

32:34.100 --> 32:54.700
Then, as he is criminal, he is selfish. And as his intellect is small, and his action is based on selfishness, he confines himself to one purpose. That purpose is remorseless. As he fled back over the Danube, leaving his forces to be cut to pieces, so now he is intent on being safe, careless of all.

32:54.700 --> 33:16.640
So his own selfishness frees my soul somewhat from the terrible power which he acquired over me on that dreadful night. I felt it! Oh, I felt it! Thank God for his great mercy! My soul is freer than it has been since that awful hour, and all that haunts me is a fear, lest in some trance or dream he may have used my knowledge for his ends.

33:17.580 --> 33:36.100
The professor stood up. He has, so used your mind. And by it he has left us here in Varna, whilst the ship that carried him rushed through enveloping fog up to Glatz, where doubtless he had made preparation for escaping from us. But his child-mind only saw so far.

33:36.100 --> 33:52.080
And it may be that as ever is in God's providence, the very thing that the evildoer most reckoned on for his selfish good turns out to be his chiefest harm. The hunter is taken in his own snare, as the great psalmist says.

33:52.080 --> 34:10.580
For now that he thinks he is free from every trace of us all, and that he has escaped us with so many hours to him, then his selfish child-brain will whisper him to sleep. He thinks, too, that as he cuts himself off from knowing your mind, there can be no knowledge of him to you, and that is where he fails.

34:10.580 --> 34:30.560
That terrible baptism of blood which he gave you makes you free to go to him in spirit, as you have yet yet done in your times of freedom when the sun rise and set. At such times you go by my volition and not by his. And this power to good of you and others you have won from your suffering at his hands.

34:31.040 --> 34:45.460
This is now all more precious that he know it not, and to God himself have even cut himself off from his knowledge of our where. We, however, are not selfish, and we believe that God is with us through all this blackness and these many dark hours.

34:46.060 --> 35:05.360
We shall follow him, and we shall not flinch, even if we peril ourselves that we become like him. Friend John, this has been a great hour, and it have done much to advance us on our way. You must prescribe and write him all down, so that when the others return from their work you can give it to them, then they shall know as we do.

35:06.060 --> 35:15.160
And so I have written it, whilst we wait their return, and Mrs. Harker has written with the typewriter all since she brought the manuscript to us.

